title: Incredible Value
text:
I bought elsewhere before I saw them here. These are top notch outer shells at an unbeatable price. Goretex is expensive, and something like this from a famous name outdoor gear collection would probably be a few hundred bucks. The quality is very good (military grade, obviously), from the materials to the zippers. The only thing I would change is adding some front "pants" pockets. Wind and waterproof, perfect for my fowl/winter weather fishing, with warm clothes underneath when needed.

I'm 6' 3" tall, 200 lbs., built long all around. I tried a large first and could just have gotten by with it, but I decided to go up to x-large and like that better. 6' 1" is probably the limit on large, maybe 6' 2" if you're not long in the torso.

Pinkalicious is funny, original, and very entertaining, even for adults. (It's one I don't mind reading over and over)

Goldilicious: 3 stars - An imaginary unicorn called Goldalicious makes for a very promising start, but then the story bogs down in repetition with not a lot of sophistication. More suited to younger kids as Pinkalicious but not as interesting.

title: This is a very impressive book.
text:
The old stories and traditions have multiple layers of meaning. Varg looks at the information that is available about the cycle of the seasons and the cycle of human life and rebirth, and explores the Ragnarök story in that context. In doing so, he maps out a coherent, integrated model for the old religion.

I am not sure that all of his premises and assumptions are completely accurate, but they work. "Accuracy" is perhaps a misleading concept anyway, because the practices of Eiríkr Þorvaldsson at Brattahlíð may have varied quite a bit from those of Hengest Wictgilsson, for example. What matters are the underlying values and beliefs. Varg has clearly done a lot of thinking about how the pieces fit together, and has produced a working model for the core mysteries. There are writers who go into specific aspects of the old religion in more depth and specificity, citing source material in a detailed way. Varg takes a different approach, and does the heavy thinking required to put it all together so that the reader can get a sense for how the religion might have functioned.

Varg seems to spend a lot of time in nature, and appears to be strongly motivated by a sense of family and tradition. One gets the sense that by living on the margins of modern European culture, he is better able than most to conceptualize the spiritual needs of our forebears, and connect what is left of the lore to these needs. I guarantee that once you read this book, you will never think about the old religion in quite the same way again.

A final note - I appreciated the rugged binding and paper of this paperback. This is a tough little book that one can stick in a jacket pocket, and pull out and read when the moment is right. An excellent formatting choice.

title: Easy and interesting read
text: 'Sorcery and Religion in Ancient Scandinavia' is the latest book from Varg Vikernes, one of the most controversial musicians of all time and the mastermind behind one of the most acclaimed black metal bands in the world – Burzum. Convicted in 1994 of the murder of band-mate Euronymous, Vikernes has since spent 15yrs studying the traditions and beliefs of the Ancient Scandinavians and their influence on modern Europeans. That research has culminated in a book in which the outspoken and often divisive author challenges many of the widely held views of contemporary culture and its history. The passionate and in-depth text provides an absorbing insight into the thoughts of this most notorious of musicians. ‘Sorcery and Religion in Ancient Scandinavia’ makes fascinating reading and will be of interest not only to black metal and Burzum fans, but also to those with an interest in Norse mythology or European history and social commentators.

title: A collector's item
text:
The author tells you outright that most of what he says is his own opinion, and that people will disagree with him. He also tells you that he'll be using a couple of books, primarily Fazer's The Golden Bough (which I've read multiple times), and his own interpretations of folklore and traditions from his upbringing to make his points. He even noted that people may not take his book seriously, or as a scholarly text, because it lacks references (it has almost none).

With that in mind I thought it was very good. The Golden Bough is 12 volumes and beyond most people's level of patience or interest. Plus it's considered dated by modern anthropologists and no longer relevant. But that's another discussion. Varg uses much of the Golden Bough to set his framework for the Northern myths and gives you the abridged version mixed with his own opinions. It's interesting to say the least, and while I don't agree with some things (I don't think Höðr is Fenrir for example), most of it is quite good and informative for a 120 page book.

I know the high cost will discourage some from getting it, but I thought it was worth it when I closed the book. I'm also very well read on the runes and Asatru, and I think his interpretations enrich the Northern Traditions instead of taking away from them.

title: "... keep reading until you realize that my interpretation is in fact correct."
text:
As with many who have purchased this book, I am a fan of Burzum's music. Motherf*cker has set himself up as some sort of messiah/martyr for his views on miscegenation and Aryan superiority, but his early nihilistic records are masterpieces and would be regardless of whether or not he was the sociopath that he happens to be. That said, let me review his book.

I will acknowledge that Varg has a passionate yet scholarly approach to his writing on sorcery and religion in proto-,bronze age, and stone age Scandinavian history/folklore. His knowledge of the subject is most likely on par with university theology professors. Unfortunately this book, despite its rigorous use of etymology to unveil Nordic myth-making practices and detailed interpretations of year round days of reverence/observations and runic interpretation is hindered by the fact that Varg doesn't cite sources to back up his claims. Part of the introduction starts the alarm bells quickly:

"The common perception of Baldr and Bragi being two separate deities for example is wrong; they are just different names
or the same deity. When you encounter such apparent "mistakes" made by me you need to accept them as correct, and
keep reading until you realise [sic] that my interpretation is in fact correct."

This in itself isn't a big deal; many scholars are trying to argue a point of view, but the biggest difference here is that Varg doesn't cite any sources to back up his claim. He didn't come by his extensive knowledge just by creating it. He did thorough research to come up with these views and wedded them to his own already controversial philosophy. He does mention that his primary sources were "The Golden Bough" by sir James Frazer and "Fedrekult i Norge" ("Ancestral Cult in Norway") by Otto Emil Berkeli, but even if those were his only two sources (which they are not), the reader needs a bibliography and source citations in text to know that the author isn't simply creating his thesis out of thin air. Don't get me wrong, I think that what Varg mentions in this book is worth the study, its just that if he would have taken another couple months to find the sources for his extensive knowledge, it would have strengthened his case.

The other problem I have with this book is Varg's proto-history interpretations. While I find the rituals that ancient man used for certain observations about the environment to bring about favorable desires fascinating, the idea that Varg can take these rituals and tell the reader the specific thoughts and desires of pre-historcic Scandinavians is problematic at best (I think people, regardless of the period they live in, are far more complex than what Varg gives them credit for) and incorrect at worst. Once again, where did he get these ideas? Is it Varg's interpretation, or has it been backed up with specific archeological/anthropological observations?

Regardless, the book is interesting and I respect how much passion he has for his subject matter. Aesthetically, he made a beautiful book: the paper/binding is high quality, as well as the prints he has unearthed. He definitely took the time with the layout to show how much he cared for this subject.

All in all, I would still recommend this book if you are a Burzum fan because it does give incite into how Varg views the world. I just wish he would have taken the extra time to cite sources for his arguments, because it would have made this book in itself a valuable resource for future historians. If you are here for scholarly knowledge, however, I am afraid there isn't any way to claim that Varg didn't just make all this sh*t up.

title: A fresh perspective
text:
Varg Vikernes' Sorcery and Religion in Ancient Scandinavia is a refreshing source of information about the beliefs in the title region. In this book, Mr. Vikernes dispels the common explanation for Ragnarok; he explains how Ragnarok and European mythology in general is misinterpreted as a linear event with a beginning and an end. Rather, he explains how Ragnarok was part of a continuing cycle like the changing seasons throughout the year.
Sorcery and Religion in Scandinavia also covers other areas, such as the Voluspa, runes and Bronze Age calendar organization. All explanations are skillfully written, keeping the reader interested throughout the book. I recommend this book to anyone who is interested in ancient European practices as well as mythology.

title: Focused, well-paced storytelling
text:
A measure of success for any author is an improvement in craft and storytelling from one book to the next. Prystauk's "Bloodletting" created characters of great distinction, and subverted the traditional notions of Noir (for as much as I love ya, I'm lookin' at you, Hard Case Crime) by making alternative-lifestyle PI Denny Bowie and his lovers, Erin and Penny, adherents of the BDSM subculture. Overall, it was a satisfying novel that teased at the possibility of a greater world of unique mysteries. Working from "Bloodletting"'s foundation, "Punishment" serves up a fresh tale that's full of page-turning intrigue. Prystauk's prose is more streamlined and engaging here, expanding on the characterizations of our central trio, and the denizens of the BDSM subculture they encounter during their investigation of a series of brutal, domme-driven murders. I was struck immediately by the focused, well-paced storytelling, which is as strategic and deliberate in establishing three-dimensional characters as it is in giving casual readers an empathetic window into alternative lifestyles. It's telling of Prystauk's own character, as creator of this world, that even moments that could have come off as cheap shock value (and there are a few humdingers in "Punishment") resonate with drama, despair, and heartbreak. Another measure of authorial success? When a slow reader like myself actively carves out time to make it just a couple pages further. Rife with suspense and unsuspecting humor, "Punishment" is a more than worthwhile trip, and I'm eager to see where Prystauk takes these characters next.

(review cross-posted from Goodreads - JGW)

A 399 page Young Adult fantasy novel. Second book of the Relics series.

This is a well written novel dealing with a young man living alone on a farm outside a forest. His brother has not returned home as expected and the young boy (Ivan) sets out to find him by entering the dangerous forest.

Essence seeking Vaguers, ravenous ratlings and evil tempered trolls cause Ivan and his forest friends all types of trouble as they attempt to locate Ivan’s brother, the missing relic and any evidence they can find that might help free a witch accused of murder. A cantankerous dragon, flying horses and crabby cat are also in the mix.

This is a good read, as was “The Long Dark Cloak”.

title: A great collection for fans of keyframe art of characters from Violet Evergarden
text:
[[ASIN:4907064829 Violet Evergarden Keyframes Collection Vol 1]] is a great gift or purchase for fans of the character art from the Kyoto Animation show on Netflix.

This is the book to buy if you are looking for keyframe art of various characters from the FIRST SIX episodes of the show. If you are looking for or hoping to see keyframe art from characters later in the season, you should look to KyoAni's [[ASIN:4907064853 Keyframes Collection Volume 2]]. This is not the book to buy if you are looking for the gorgeous background art, preliminary concept art, or fully “composed” frames of still scenes from the show. For those looking for a book of conceptual art and design for the show, you should look to KyoAni’s [[ASIN:4907064802 Violet Evergarden Chronicle [official fan book]]].

Similarly, because these are keyframes, the artwork is not yet filled with the vibrant colors from the finished show. But this may be what makes this book an ideal gift or item to have for fan. At a hefty 150 pages on good paper stock, you will find page after page of characters from the show like Violet, Gilbert Bougainvillea, Erica Brown, etc. The keyframe art is also neatly organized by episode so it is easy to find characters and particular keyframes from each episode as you look through the book.

Viewers who are particularly impressed by the quality of the art and animation of the show will not be disappointed as you will find in this book some particularly striking keyframe poses: Violet removing her gloves with her teeth, closeups of her hands, the room of students learning to be “Auto Memory Dolls,” Cattelya Baudelaire smirking in a scene with Claudia Hodgins, etc. Fans will be happy to know that you will be likely to find key or iconic character scenes here in some form in this keyframe art book.

title: The London System at its finest!
text: An amazing read.  The London System as a weapon against 1...d5 exclusively has taught me so much in just the 2 weeks that I have owned it.  This book can teach an amateur player about playing chess, especially Queen Pawn systems,  just as much as it can teach the London System itself.  Nikola Sedlak's introduction says it all.  He states that while every chess player is searching for an opening system that suits them, he has always been happy with his openings against 1...Nf6 systems, as they provide plenty of imbalanced positions.  However, what to do about 1...d5?  Positions from the Slav and the Queen's Gambit can be such impenetrable fortresses.  During his search for the right weapon, he researched the games of Tony Miles, England's first over the board Grandmaster.  Sedlak includes many of his own games against strong GM competition, along with several games by Croatian GM Vlatko Kovacevic, Eric Prie, and correspondence with Hungarian star Ferenc Berkes, the writer has created a deep, dynamic repertoire from the London System.  Each chapter, separated by theme, with a special chapter on London Endgames, makes this book, and this system, so much more complete than any other London book I have.  Though I would recommend Play the London System by Lakdawala, and Win with the London System by Kovacevic himself, this book, Winning with the Modern London System is by far the most complete teacher of all the London System books.  There are some real long term weapons here.

title: The author has written a pretty good book but I have found at least one ...
text:
I have just about all the material in English on the London. What I have found is that each book has lapses and oversights. And each has strong points. The author has written a pretty good book but I have found at least one point I disagree with him on. He says that in the line 1.d4 d5, 2. Bf4 Bf5, 3. e3 e6, 4. c4 when Bxb1 followed by Bb4+ forces the king to move losing the right to castle is just dandy for white. I disagree. Instead of 3. e3 white should play 3. c4 immediately allowing the Bishop to return if needed preserving the right to castle.
Still, one of the best books on the London and well worth buying.
I want to add some further thoughts about this book. This book takes the point of view that the London is best played against the move order 1. d4 d5. And that the London is a poor choice versus the Kings Indian Defense. I happen to agree, so this book is a nice fit for my repertoire. It also means the author is able to focus on a much narrower cluster of variations, which he then proceeds to break down and analyse in detail, beyond anything I have in any other book. If you play the London, I consider this book a must have.

title: Excellent contents except for translation miscues
text: This is a very good book, as long as you can overlook the translation oddities. The translator seemed to prefer the more convoluted present and past progressive tenses rather than the simpler and easier to understand present and past tenses, for example, "is always winning" or "is losing". "Always wins" and "loses" are more natural English expressions. There are typographical and grammatical mistakes on almost every page (i have only read about 40 pages so far). "queenendgames" seems like something you would concatenate in German, not English; this occurs a number of times, so I don't think it was accidental. But the organization of the book and the variation notes are first-rate. Practical examples and theoretical positions are intermingled, and the authors freely admit in some of the notes that Queen endgames are often understandable only to computers; it takes several tries, for me at least, to get the idea of what is going on, or supposed to be going on, in some of the positions. The best thing I can say is that I will buy the subsequent books in this series even if the translations don't improve.

title: Difficult but rewarding
text:
The overwhelming majority of the combinations in this edition have been culled from past issues of Chess Informant -- i.e., from grandmaster praxis of the last four decades. The combinations are not easy and I think a player should be at least Class A (i.e. USCF 1800+) to be able to use the book -- though I think the target readership is probably at least expert (USCF 2000+). For pedagogical purposes the first edition which came out in 1980 was far superior. This edition is designed as training material for the advanced player.

The classification pattern has reverted to one similar to the first edition (i.e., themes of deflection, pinning, double attack, clearance, interference, decoy, blockade, demolition of pawn structure, annihilation of defence) with the important caveat that at the GM level these don't have much meaning as the combinations typically rely on a number of themes and the classification can be arbitrary.

The quality of the binding is good as is the quality of the paper. 3,001 combinations and their solutions take up 659 pages.

To reiterate, if you're a strong player looking for some training material to hone your already formidable tactical skill, this book might be appropriate. Weaker players would probably be advised to stay away.

title: Not for first timers or those looking for formulations and proofs.
text: This is a pretty standard text in many great physics programs. My professor specifically selected with book for my grad level course because top universities use it. However, i found it less approachable than it is comprehensive. More approachable than Jackson by a long shot without Jackson's attitude. But, I find it much less thorough than a text like Jackson, Sakurai, or even Shankar. This textbook felt sort of like a survey of statistical mechanics for those who already know much of it and have the math skills to fill in a lot of gaps. I do not recommend this book for someone trying to learn it for the first time. It offers a dialogue on the vast uses and subjects in statistical mechanics rather than mathenaticsl proofs or formulations of the fundamental theories. I like it for the conversations about statistical mechanics and the number of equations in it across many fields inside of stat mech.

title: Useful, but not ideal
text:
My son and I just spent two weeks in Israel with a rental car. This atlas was very good for the place-to-place driving, but not helpful for local driving once we got to a place. For that we relied on an endless supply of print-offs of Google maps. So, for peace of mind getting from Caesarea to Zippori to Tiberias, etc., and finding some specific sites that don't require local maps (e.g., Chorazin, Tel Dan, Banias), this was an essential purchase for driving in Israel; for utility at any one of those places rather than the in-between roads, it was not helpful at all. As other reviewers have mentions, it's scale is also too small to be used comfortably if you have anything but eagle eyes. Take out the pages on the 100 best sites (for which there are better tour books anyway) and give us some city maps; re-print in at least 8.5x11 format.

I do have to say that the price tag is nowhere near the value of this resource when it is set alongside a 2017 US Road Atlas (printed large, containing many city insets). It's a specialty item, admittedly, but we pay for this beyond its value.

Unrelated to review but perhaps useful to visitors driving in Israel: I found route numbers to be used less consistently in Jerusalem than indications by city name/suburb name concerning where a particular turn-off headed. Just a caution, as this proved quite stressful. Also, take into account the fact that the terrain is INCREDIBLY three-dimensional (unlike most of Florida, for example). A road atlas, of course, can't prepare you for the amount of vertical distance you'll be traveling up and down from place to place.

title: Splendid Theatrical Opera and Metal
text:
The title of this album, which translates to The Diary of Hanna Anikin, is based on a short story that the founder of this band, Michael Haas, wrote. Its a brilliantly composed and beautifully executed album that one could never become sick of!
This album, as well as the band themselves, faced a bit of a problem when the album was being marketed toward the death metal and black metal crowds. While this album certainly has elements of metal with the distorted guitar riffs in the background, it shouldn't be confused with a typical metal album. It is much better composed and much more in-depth. However, if you're looking for true black metal with classical composition, check out early works by Satyricon or Darkthrone.
The classical pieces and the opera vocals are more theatrical in style - they weren't meant to be perfect, however, to the untrained ear they do sound perfect. Each track has perfect balance and the end of every track and the beginning of a new one actually flows the way the turning of a page would.
I would only recommend this album for people who would welcome variety in the music that they listen to. If you're looking for straight death metal or black metal, then you might not like this album if you haven't heard samples. Also if you're a fan of this band, take the time to write to the founder, Michael Haas. He actually takes the time to write back to you!

What I love about this glider is that it is great quality. . . glides smoothly, locks when you don't want it to glide, relaxes you with comfy cushions (like the arm cushions since I breastfeed -cushions kind of "squeak" though when you sit on them), arm rests are at a good height for me, the color fits into our nursery scheme, and it has a matching ottoman that you can purchase to go along with it.

What bothers me about this ottoman is that it's not really very wide in the seat! Sounds crazy, I know. I'm not a large person, but I'm also not petite. Seems that there is another glider out there that would be the perfect, comfortable width. But you'd probably have to pay more. This glider is worth the money despite the width!

title: Wonderful Glider!
text:
Our old glider was awful! It whined and squeaked and the padding wore down after a few months of use.

This glider is a dream. It can be locked into several positions, the padding is nice and the arms are padded (which saves getting indentations in your arms if you are nursing for a while or rocking a little one to sleep). There is no awful noise, it's sturdy and it sits up high enough that it's not a struggle to get out holding a sleeping baby.

We sat in every glider that the store had, ones far more expensive than this one as well as cheaper and I found that I liked this chair the best. One drawback is that it's narrower than a lot of other chairs so the fit is snug (I believe that it's mainly due to the padding on the arms and the sides) but unless you are very large it shouldn't be a problem and a personal test sit of the chair, if you can manage it, is a nice thing to do anyway.

title: Update
text:
I wrote a review earlier, and I just wanted to update. I absolutely LOVE this rocker. I breastfeed my baby, so I've been using this AT LEAST 8 times a day for feedings, I use it more than that when I also use it to rock baby to sleep. It's held up extremely well thus far. The cushioning is still puffy, comfortable, and substantial, it almost "holds" you while you are sitting in it, you feel really snug.
One caveat, you will not be able to use the breast/bottle feeding pillows like Boppy or My Brest Friend because of this cushioning feature. What I've done is use a regular bedpillow folded in half to hold up baby's head, and then have her legs draped over the arm cushions (I do the football/clutch hold for positioning). Other times when I've done crade or cross cradle position, her body is completely on the folded bedpillow and her belly up against mine, it's worked out fine. Another plus is when I'm rocking her to sleep, I have her laid out in my lap, and her head resting on the arm cushion, it's great for giving your arms a break from all the holding.
I commented previously about the denim fabric pilling from the first use. The funny thing is, the pilling is now gone! I think the fabric just had a fine layer that it needed to "shed", it looks totally fine now.
My in-laws own a Dutailer glider, and I can honestly say, they are similar. I used the Dutailer every time we've gone to visit, and I made a conscious effort to take notes of any differences, there really aren't any, except maybe for price? I read the other review about the "lemon" of a chair that person got. That must have been a spoof chair, so that may be a problem if the quality isn't consistent. I guess I got lucky and got a good one. In the end, I'm very happy with this purchase, I love the white wood, and again, it's a great Dutailer alternative.

title: Great set!
text: We purchased a toddler bed and the Elmo bedding set this weekend. The print is really a cute one, and it seemed to help our son to want to be in his Elmo "big boy bed". The quality of the stuff turned out to be terrific. I was truly surprised at the softness of not only the sheets and pillow case, but of the comforter as well. title: Sturdy but has problems
text:
Eastpak Mastermind is quite a sturdy knapsack.
I use it to carry items to and from work. It does a great job
in holding my lunch, books, folded jacket, notebooks, keys..etc.
Most sacks I've had don't handle the weight that well, especially if you are a college student. I have actually had a knapsack rip apart at the seems under the weight off all the text books I'm carrying. Eastpak doesn't have that problem.
Also wearing an Eastpak on your back is quite gentle. The straps and backing are foam, so it's easy on the back and shoulders. The knapsacks material is also pretty water repellent. I've gone through more than my share of being stuck in the middle of a torrential downpour, the outside of my knapsack is soaked, but the contest were bone dry.
My only negative comment about Eastpak is the no-slip straps.
They should be called "always-slip". I've threaded the straps every which way and they've always come undone under the most light weight carrying conditions. I've ended up knotting the end of the strap so it doesn't slip through. Really not astetically pleasing, but it got the job done. My only real issue with this fine bag.
For the college student on the go, or for the white collar worker rushing to and from work, I believe Eastpak is a good buy with some minor reservations.

title: Amazing capacity and very confortable!
text:
I used to be a very loyal Jansport buyer, but when the time came for a new backpack, I decided to see what else was out there. I am very glad I did.

I knew this was the backpack for me when I was in a store examining the various models and trying them on for comfort. After about half an hour of this I decided to go do some other shopping when my daughter pointed out I still had one on my shoulder! It fit so well that I had stopped noticing I even had it on. So I bought it!

The Pros:

- Two very roomy main compartments that inhale a stack of books and notebooks with no problem. Since there are two, it let me be a little more organized about what contents go in which one.

- Padded notebook sleeve. I've only carried mine a few times in there, but it felt reasonably padded from routine handling, but I'd still take care in tossing the backpack around.

- Convenient set of various pockets on the front. I quickly assigned each of these specific roles (cell phone in the top one; pda in another; spare batteries, keys, and bus map in a third, etc.) Being able to go right to a specific compartment was nicer than rummaging around for stuff.

- Comfy top handle. It has a very nice rubberized top handle for those times when you don't want to or can't shoulder-carry it, the handgrip is nice and cozy. In my opinion it's far nicer than merely padded hand straps that still cut into your hands after a while.

- Rugged! I've loaded rather large piles of computer science books into it and was likely to have my back itself give out before the backpack would. I used to go through a Jansport every few semesters (usually from splitting at the seams somewhere) but this Eastpak still looks new after a year of daily use.

The Con:

- It lacks any sort of water-bottle holder. If you have something insulated that doesn't sweat, you could put it inside, but that's not always an option. It's just a shame they didn't add some netted ones on the sides. It would have made this an ultimate backpack if it just had that.

So I've found my new favorite backpack from this (and I've been through a dozen or so in my life) and become a new Eastpak fan in the process. For the price, I haven't found anything on the market that comes close to this for my needs.

title: These socks are golden!!
text:
Socks seem like a strange kind of thing on which to write a review, but these socks are special. I placed an order for a friend of mine who runs a soup kitchen in Poplar Bluff Missouri. It was an order of about 60 pairs of these socks which probably seemed pretty strange to the people at Sportsman's Guide, but they sent them anyway. I didn't think much about it until I got an e-mail from Joni, the lady in Poplar Bluff, that the socks had arrived.
She told me that you would think that the socks were made of gold the way the people at her free store responded to them. They had NEVER seen such socks!! They were soft and they were thick and warm. Most of them had never even heard of wool socks.
Now I don't think twice about wool socks because I love them but it gave me real pause to think that there were people who had never even heard of such a wonderful thing. These people couldn't believe that someone would just give them something this good. Yes, this good.
So if you're thinking of buying some of these why don't you get an extra pair or two and give them to someone who needs them. It will be an education, I promise, and your gift will reward you many times over when you experience the gratitude such a small thing can evoke.

title: Big, Hard to Use, Easy to Read - A Study in Contradictions
text:
First of all, it works, but it's almost like it has to learn where the radio tower is before it can set the time -- took several days before it began to receive a strong signal.

According to the mileage calculator at:
[...]
I'm about 1200 miles from the transmitter as the crow flies. This could have been sun spots; who knows? After "training" the watch has updated every night as per claims.

It's a BIG watch. It doesn't look too big in the mirror, but it looks big to me when I look down. Also, my shirt cuffs won't pass over it.

If you have ever worked on your car with a digital watch on, you will know why the push buttons are protected on this watch. There is absolutely no way you can press a button accidentally. There is almost no way you can press one intentionally, as well. Whoever designed this watch had tiny fingers. I suspect that part of the klutziness is because the buttons protect a water proof seal in order to meet the depth rating claimed.

I keep a specially shaped thumb nail handy in case I want to push a button to find out something in addition to the time and date. This is unfortunate because the watch is full of special functions that could be useful if one could get at them easier. The functions are in reverse order of how I would use them. First comes time zone, then stored times, followed by alarms, then the timer. You can't use most of these without the manual, so the difficulty of pushing the buttons is almost irrelevant.

The blue color is a nice touch. The strap and case are what I would call "midnight blue" with just hints of powder blue around the silver colored bezel. The blue lends some class to a plastic covered watch, in my opinion.

A big plus is that the digital display is easy to read without reading glasses because of the BIG numbers. For this reason alone, I will keep it.

title: Pros outweigh the cons...
text:
I actually bought the black version of this watch, but the site no longer lists that version so I'll put my thoughts here...

First, the Pros &amp; Cons...

Pros:
------
- Syncs to the Atomic signal for ultra accurate time keeping
- Solar Powered
- BIG display with BIG characters, nothing more than a quick glance is needed to get the info you need
- Auto-Illumination, in dimlit situations when you turn the watch towards your face it auto-illuminates.
- True to being a G-Shock, it's a thick and beefy watch and even the band is extra thick...Definitely has the G-Shock 'feel'

Cons:
------
- SWEAT! Also true to the G-Shock legacy is how this watch causes a sweaty wrist. This watch is even more prone to causing sweat from it's especially thick plastic band.
- Hard to get at recessed buttons
- No countdown timer

This is my 3rd G-Shock (gave my first to my brother, the 2nd I wore out the band and just threw it away instead of dealing with getting a new band). I bought it because the aspect of having a G-Shock that synced with the Atomic Signal was very appealing and having it be Solar Powered was a big bonus. I am NOT sorry for buying this watch!

I wanted an impervious-to-everyday-wear-n-tear, accurate, easy to read display and this watch fits the bill and then some. Though the recessed buttons are actually annoying to access, I don't use the other modes all that often so it's not that big a problem for me.

Great watch, I've already recommended it to a few friends

title: Slice & Dice: Learning to love your Inner Slasher
text:
Remember that scene from "Hannibal" where the depraved and obsessive billionaire Mason Verger, horribly mutilated by his own hand and Hannibal Lecter's powerful psychosis, bought Hannibal's protective mask from the flesh-chewing Good Doctor's former orderly?

Verger paid a few million for the privilege of wearing a brilliant but mortal serial killer's mask. I paid 150 bucks and got an immortal slasher's hockey mask, made from sturdy, battle-scarred resin, and bolted into place against lush blood-red velvet backing in its ominous black shadowbox. I mounted it by a bookshelf in one of the darkened corners of my study, and I tell ya---sometimes I fancy I can see crazed, darting eyes glaring out at me from the dark orbs of that infamous Hockey Mask.

And as I said, where poor Mason Verger paid a mint to get Hannibal's mask, I get Jason's mask *and* bloodthirsty revenant Freddy Krueger's deadly claw of leather and steel (alright, alright---plastic, resin, and rubber---but a man can dream). Bear in mind that while the glove has heft as well---even if it doesn't have retractable steel blades, which was what I was counting on---you can't remove it from the box without a screwdriver. Doubtless NECA, visions of 2,000 blade-gloved maniacs prowling the countryside and the inevitable lawsuits in mind, decided on plastic over flesh-ripping steel, but I'm still happy with the finished product.

So go ahead, summon up the Mask & Glove. I'm jaded, and it was my favorite gift (to myself) in the last decade. Buy it, hang it on the wall, and give a little love to your inner Slasher.

title: Well-designed and spacious but with stiff zippers
text:
See update below.

This pack is well designed overall although the zippers could be improved. The rectangular shape provides much greater actual capacity than the styles that are shaped like a shallow or wide "V". An eyeglasses case can almost stand up inside the main compartment.

The outer nylon fabric seems very sturdy although only time will tell for sure.

The one design flaw I see is the zippers. They are stiff and tight. They do not zip open and closed easily. Some take two hands - one to pinch the fabric behind the szipper and the other to pull the zipper handle. Zippers are more effective when they easily pull open or closed. I lubricated two of the zippers with some solid silicone lubricating stick and this seemed to help quite a lot.

I would probably buy it again although I must admit that I would look around first for similar styles with smoother zippers.

Update after using for several months.

The stiff zippers got annoying. I purchased some High Sierra lumbar packs that are equally or more spacious, have smooth-operating zippers, have more pockets, and have more-friendly features such as clip loops, key ring clips, cell phone/MP3 player cord access. See:
Passport: [[ASIN:B000P583AY High Sierra Passport Lumbar Pack]]
Express: [[ASIN:B002YQ628W High Sierra Express Waist Packs]]
Envoy: [[ASIN:B000P5A726 High Sierra Envoy Lumbar Pack]]

title: Easy to use
text:
Let's face it, if someone actually steals your bag they will find a way to get in, even if means destroying the bag. The TSA approval means that the security people can open the lock if they need to inspect something. I'm not saying the security check issue is a major problem but after you check your bag, and it goes through the security check, it will be sitting around waiting to be loaded or in transit from one flight to the next.

This type of lock is to deter the casual thief from going through you bag when left unattended. I decided that a combo lock was better than a key lock (lost key) and 4 dials were better than 3. This eBags lock is designed to work for the most common bags sold these days, is easy to use and it is easy to reset the combination.

Just remember to twirl the dials after you lock it :o).

title: A Wonderful Purchase
text:
I received this bag about a year and half ago, and it is great. I am able to fit my flute, piccolo, cell phone, wallet, collapsible music stand, and sheet music into it. The stand stick out a little bit, but it is only a slight danger to other people around you.
It has a very nice appearance, most of my section in band has asked were I purchased it to ask their parents to purchase one for themselves.
There are two pockets on the front that close with velcro. They can fit a lot of stuff into them. The back zipper pocket is large and can accommodate a piccolo and stand in it, along with pencils. There are two inside pockets along with the space for the flute. One is mesh and the other is fully enclosed. They both are the full length of the front flap, top and back of the bag. The closure for the front works well, and is easy to use. The length can to shortened or made longer to allow as much stuff as possible to be stuffed into it. I can normally fit a 1,000 page book resting on the buckle.
There was only a slight problem when the plastic findings on the strap broke. All I had to do was call Pro-tec, and they sent me another strap, with metal findings instead of plastic. They did not even ask that you send back the broken part.

title: Excellent product with a few glitches
text:
This is an almost perfect daily-use fanny pack --- highly functional (with seven zippered pockets and an exterior mobile phone pocket with velcro-closure) and very attractive.

My only real complaint is that the zippers aren't great quality. On my first AmeriLeather Leather Cell Pone Fanny Pack, after not even two years of use, one zipper broke. (It was the one that gets used the most, since it's on the pocket where I keep my keys.) Otherwise, though, I'm so pleased with this fanny pack that I ordered it again to replace the one w/the broken zipper. (I'll take that one to a shoe repair shop and get the zipper fixed, so I'll be ready when a zipper breaks on the new one!)

There is also a little problem with the buckle, but it's pretty easy to resolve. Basically, the way it is attached to the strap makes it really hard to adjust, and since fanny pack straps need to be adjusted pretty often (to accommodate the various layers of clothing worn under the pack), hassle-free adjustment is pretty crucial. This problem isn't too hard to fix. You just cut the strap to remove the buckle and feed the strap through the right way; however, you have to be careful to put the buckle on in the right orientation (with the ridged side of the cross-piece facing upward), or the strap won't stay at the right length. (The way the buckle was originally attached, changing the strap length is too complicated, but if you fix it wrong, the strap won't stay at the length you set it at; it will slide bigger and bigger.)

title: Not the item pictured.
text:
First off, this seller has a lot of gall to put a photo of the glasses that does not match the actual item delivered (whether or not either set of glasses resemble the one Agent Smith wore is another issue).

Now, I was not expecting a high quality replica, it's twenty bucks, but I at least wanted to receive the item depicted on the sales listing.

Noticeable differences:

1)the nose piece looks very different, and is not attached to the glases frames/lenses by brackets, as depicted.

2)The glasses are cheaply and shoddily mirrored, rather than being tinted dark, as depicted.

title: Sadly, Silver Forest has gone downhill
text: Over quite a few years I've bought and worn Silver Forest jewelry, especially earrings, and used to get so many compliments on them.  Unfortunately, their aesthetic has changed over time, away from what made their pieces special and interesting.  Many of their designs used to be kind of contemporary and unusual, with the multiple, individually moving components, contrasting materials and textures, and subtle color palettes creating a unique feel.  They were sort of sophisticated but relatively affordable.  Some designs veered more towards conventionally pretty or delicate, while some were more like abstract modern art pieces, but all were pretty well made and special.  These days, it seems they go more towards an overly "pretty" aesthetic, too overwhelmingly using motifs such as lace, flowers, tear-drop shapes, and such, all made with less interesting materials.  Such things are not bad, necessarily, but the variety is gone, and their pieces are just not very special anymore.  I'm very disappointed and will probably not seek out their products as I have over the years.  Too bad.

title: The King. I'm serious.
text:
I have owned just about every kind of work gloves you can imagine over the years, and after moving onto a property 15 years ago that is overrun with multiflora rose, I made it my mission to find a pair of gloves that lasted and that I could work in. Maybe 6 months out of the year I am ripping out wild rosebushes to keep trails and lawns clear and then there are all of the other things that need to be done when you live in the country. I have shredded every so called indestructible glove, often in a day, getting them replaced under warranty and shredding the replacement. I started doing some searching and eventually found some little corner of the web where people were singing the praises of this roping glove that bikers liked for its thick elkskin leather and form fit, so much so that the company made a variation with a little integrated squeegee to help wipe rain from their visors. Long story short, I am here writing a review for a product that isn't currently available, looking around for a pair to buy my father as a gift, because when I got the Geiers, after a couple of wears the fit was like it was made for my hand(and the snap back is a big part of that) and the thick elkskin protects me from the thorns, barbed wire, and anything else I throw at it while allowing me to do an awful lot without having to remove them. No lining, nothing else to break down, and the comfort that comes from that simplicity is considerable.

I know what it sounds like and I swear I'm just a happy customer. And in 15 years of yanking out thornbushes and everything else... I'm on my second pair of gloves. So I feel like all around it's been a pretty good deal. Now if I can just find a pair before the holidays. No luck here and no Geier retailers in western NY. Anyway, assuming they'll be back in stock here, buy em or don't buy em - you know what I think, and the reviews on this product are a bit more balanced befitting one of the few products I've come across that made no grand claims, just went ahead and over delivered on every count.

title: Reliable as a hammer
text:
If you want a plain, no frills watch that keeps perfect time, look no further. I've had several of these over the past 20 years, and will never change models as long as Timex keeps making these.

Pro:
1. They keep perfect time, within seconds per month. I've set mine to the atomic clock at NIST and checked it a month or so later, and its right on.

2. The Indiglo feature is, for me, a "can't do without". Not only is it handy for checking the time in the dark, it serves as an "always available" flashlight for finding the keyhole for your car door key and will keep you from walking into things if you have to get up in the middle of the night.

3. Battery life is extremely good. I often get a year or more from a battery. Wal-Mart will install a new one for you at no charge if you buy the battery there.

Con: The calendar feature is a pain to set, and you have to reset it whenever the new month has a different number of days from the previous month.

Summary:
This is a geat product that indeed meets Timex's slogan of "Takes a licking and keeps on ticking" although it doesn't really tick.

title: Attractive Style & Size, Not Substantial Weight
text: I recently visited a labyrinth that was perched in a very scenic spot overlooking the Golden Gate Bridge. Because the visit was so perfect I wanted some symbol to remember it by. This necklace is what I chose. The design is attractive and I like the silver tone (vs a gold). And the size is just right - big enough to see what it is but not so big that you feel you're wearing a small manhole cover around your neck. It's just that the pendant could have had more heft to it weight-wise based on what the photo suggested. A more high quality piece wouldn't be quite this light. The black cord also makes it look more like something you'd buy in a souvenir shop. But if you swap it out for a silver chain it will be more attractive and gift-like. The black cord lets you adjust the length. The seller also provides a nice little jewelry pouch that is great for storing or presenting the necklace. And they were very responsive wrt shipping - which I consider a must for anyone (including Amazon) selling on the Amazon site. So my rating is not saying the product is bad, just average. More weight to the pendant would have equalled 4 stars. That weight plus a silver chain (vs the black cord) would have made it 5 stars.

title: Great NeckLace
text:
I bought this necklace back in 2010 (Seems like it was a lot longer ago) The necklace had been through a lot in the first year I owned it. I had to go through a lot of medical testing and the necklace was a special gift I bought myself at the start of it all. There where points where I would bite on it to keep from screaming out in pain. And all that happened to the necklace was a tiny dent.
The only thing that didn't hold up was the string that held the necklace together. When it started to fall apart I put it away for safe keeping but have since lost it.
So if you're looking at this necklace as an everyday necklace, let me tell you if it can hold up under a painful search for cancer (that later came up negative) it will hold up in everyday wear.

title: I don't get it...
text: I am assuming from the other reviews here that this is supposed to be some covert Satanic symbol...but what it is actually is a copy of the symbol belonging to the band Blue Oyster Cult, one of the originators of heavy metal.  The symbol is derived from the hook and cross, symbol of Kronos (Greek titan, father of Zeus), Saturn, and the alchemical representation of lead (a "heavy metal").  The symbol as represented in this pendant--with the dot at the cross center--is BOC's trademark exactly.  I find it amusing that people that belong to a demographic that I'm guessing wasn't even born yet during the 1970's are running around with a trademark from a sci-fi/fantasy metal band while thinking that they are making a hushed anti-Christian statement.  Don't believe it? Search BOC on the web and read about the derivation of the symbol...
